entry.title: Limit TLS-is-destroyed to ThreadChecker slow path
entry.content:
This prevents TLS-is-destroyed calls unless the sequence token doesn't

match and would've failed unless TLS has been destroyed. A TODO is left

here, like in SequenceChecker, to see if we can remove this destroyed

check completely.



This change has a behavior change that `task_token_` matching

TaskToken::GetForCurrentThread() will be accepted only if `task_token_`

is valid (not if `task_token_` and TaskToken::GetForCurrentThread() are

both invalid) and will also pass regardless of TLS-destruction state.



EnsureAssigned() was previously avoided during TLS shutdown since

reading TLS at that point would be undefined. The current

SequenceToken is now stored in a `thread_local` which no longer exhibits this destruction-order issue, so we EnsureAssigned()

unconditionally.



Bug: 1372121

entry.title: Update server_redirect_urls for retargeting navigations
entry.content:
In a retargeting navigation, we can't trust the original destination.

This includes the server_redirect_urls. The current code attempts to

correct for that by including the search_url in the

server_redirect_urls, but this is not correct for two reasons:

- It still includes server_redirect_urls from the retargeting navigation

that never happened

- It does not include server_redirect_urls from the true navigation.



Instead we should replace the retargeting navigation events

server_redirect_urls with the true navigation's redirects.

entry.title: SyncServiceImpl::GetModelTypesForTransportOnlyMode(): Include NIGORI
entry.content:
SyncServiceImpl::GetModelTypesForTransportOnlyMode() returns the set of

types that are supported in transport-only mode.

Before this CL, the returned set didn't include NIGORI (even though

NIGORI *is* supported in transport-only mode). This had little

practical impact, since NIGORI isn't configured along with other data

types anyway - however, it *did* affect the "interested data types" for

entry.title: Implemented wait for model availability and timeout on RequestDispatcher
entry.content:
Segmentation server-side models need to be loaded from disk or

network before they can be executed. Right now RequestDispatcher

doesn't take this into consideration when enqueueing requests, so they

may get dispatched before their model is ready.



This CL modifies RequestDispatcher to keep a list of models that

are yet to be loaded, and enqueues all requests that involve

those models. It also adds an OnModelUpdated listener to RequestDispatcher, this gets called when a model gets loaded or

updated and it's used to dispatch all requests for the model that is

ready.



There's also a timeout in case a model takes too long to load, or

when there's no model available.

entry.title: Android: Skip bytecode checks for prebuilt jars
entry.content:
Generated prebuilt targets like the ones in //third_party/android_deps

and //third_party/androidx have their own list of generated deps. They

often omit deps that Chromium doesn't use. Whenever they are missing a

direct dep, we simply add the GN arg to skip the target instead.



This CL proactively skips bytecode checks for direct deps and relies on

TraceReferences to catch any actually missing classes. This paves the

way for using a more thorough checker (jdeps) for enforcing direct deps.

entry.title: [sync] Stop using IsSyncRequested for DISABLE_REASON_USER_CHOICE
entry.content:
A new approach is introduced, that leverages the state reported by

IdentityManager, when it comes to determining whether SyncService should

list DISABLE_REASON_USER_CHOICE among the reasons why sync-the-feature

is disabled.



The new logic is guarded with a kill switch but otherwise enabled by

default, as it is assumed that in practice both implementations should

be equivalent.



ChromeOS Ash is special-cased because there is a platform-specific

scenario where the sync-requested bit is needed. Namely, this is for

the case where the Sync server reports DISABLE_SYNC_ON_CLIENT (e.g.

data cleared via Sync dashboard).
